han good enough because there will always be accidents and tragedies beyond our control, which is why we must stop dividing the world into winners and losers and ensure that there is a fair share of decency and sufficiency to go around.Visionary and provocative, The Good-Enough Life demonstrates how we can work together to cultivate a good-enough life for all instead of tearing ourselves apart in a race to the top of the social pyramid.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aAbility. 0aConduct of life. 0aSelf-realization. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Social.2bisacsh  aAbleism.  aAbsurdity.  aAdolf Hitler.  aAfrican-American Civil Rights Movement (1954–68).  aAgriculture (Chinese mythology).  aArbitrariness.  aArchaeology.  aAttention economy.  aBiomass (ecology).  aBuddhism.  aCanberra.  aCapitalism.  aCentral Asia.  aChengdu.  aCompany.  aCompetition.  aComputational model.  aCory Doctorow.  aCustomer.  aCycling.  aDeansgate.  aDebt.  aDisability studies.  aDocking station.  aEconomic recovery.  aEconomics.  aElitism.  aEntrepreneurship.  aEqual opportunity.  aFeeling.  aFiat money.  aFinancial institution.  aFunding.  aGlobal warming.  aGood and evil.  aGreat Famine (Ireland).  aGreatness.  aHinge.  aHuman migration.  aHuman nature.  aHumility.  aHunter-gatherer.  aIllustration.  aImperialism.  aIncome bracket.  aJacques Derrida.  aLaptop.  aLaughter.  aLiberal socialism.  aLocal community.  aLoneliness.  aMarket (economics).  aMechanization.  aMentorship.  aMeritocracy.  aMichael Walzer.  aMining.  aMoisture.  aMorality.  aMutual aid (organization theory).  aNetflix.  aNew Society.  aNew Urbanism.  aNikil Saval.  aPali Canon.  aPatriarchy.  aPerfectionism (psychology).  aPlay (activity).  aPosit